\description{
A small, self-contained set of dplyr-style verbs for building a SQL query against the
\code{obis} view step by step. Unlike \link[duckplyr:duckplyr-package]{duckplyr::duckplyr}, this does not attempt to translate general
R data-manipulation semantics through a relational engine, which does not cope well with
this dataset's deeply nested \code{interpreted}/\code{extensions} struct columns -- it is a thin,
literal R-expression-to-SQL-text translator instead. Nothing is executed until
\code{\link[=collect_db]{collect_db()}} (or \code{\link[=show_sql]{show_sql()}}, which only prints the query).

Revisited: \code{duckplyr}'s \code{dd::unnest()} does let plain \code{dplyr::select()}/\code{filter()}
reach the flat \code{interpreted}/\code{source} structs directly, with full DuckDB pushdown --
but it doesn't reach the \code{extensions} struct-of-list-of-struct (still needs the same
flattening \code{.sql_extension_select()} does), can't call arbitrary DuckDB/extension SQL
functions at all (\code{ST_Intersects}, \verb{h3_*} -- there is no escape hatch, it's a hard R
error), and silently materializes the \emph{entire} table into R on any unsupported
operation. That's not a fit for this dataset's scale, so this file remains the
supported query path; see \code{\link[=to_duckplyr]{to_duckplyr()}} for an explicitly experimental alternative.

\code{select_db()}, \code{mutate_db()}, \code{filter_db()}, \code{group_by_db()},
\code{summarize_db()}/\code{summarise_db()}, and \code{collect_db()} are named with a \verb{_db} suffix
(rather than the bare dplyr verb names) specifically so they are never masked by
\code{dplyr::filter()}/\code{mutate()}/etc. when both packages are attached.

\code{select_db()} \emph{replaces} the select list (like \code{dplyr::select()}), while \code{mutate_db()}
\emph{appends} to whatever is currently selected (starting from \code{*} by default). Since the
underlying \code{interpreted}/\code{source}/\code{extensions} structs are very wide, an unnarrowed
\verb{select *} can be slow to materialize -- call \code{select_db()} before \code{collect_db()} to
name only the fields you need.
}
\details{
Bare symbols in an expression (e.g. \code{interpreted.depth}) are treated as column
identifiers, \emph{unless} a variable of that name exists in the calling environment, in
which case its value is evaluated and inlined as a SQL literal (or an \code{IN} list, for a
vector) -- e.g. \verb{depth_limit <- 100; filter_db(con, interpreted.depth <= depth_limit)}.
Because the dataset's real fields are qualified names like \code{interpreted.depth}, which
are never plausible variable names, this rarely creates ambiguity in practice; it can in
principle shadow an \emph{unqualified} top-level column (\code{id}, \code{flags}, \code{dropped}, \code{absence})
if a same-named variable happens to be in scope.

Known limitations: \code{filter_db()} always emits to \code{WHERE} (no post-aggregation \code{HAVING}
support); \code{group_by_db()} replaces the grouping columns on each call and only takes
effect once \code{summarize_db()}/\code{summarise_db()} is called; two \code{summarize_db()} calls in
one chain are not supported (no subquery nesting); \code{^}, \code{\%\%}, \code{\%/\%} are not translated.
}
